%N A397000 Square array A(n,k), n >= 1, k >= 0, read by antidiagonals downwards, where column k is the expansion of e.g.f. F^k(x), where F(x) is the e.g.f. of A396996.
%F A397000 E.g.f. F(x) satisfies F'(x) = exp(F^l(x)), where F^l(x) denotes the l-th iterate of F, with F(0) = 0.
%F A397000 Let a(n,k,l) = n! * [x^n] F^k(x), where F^k(x) is the k-th iterate of F, and let b(n,k,l) = n! * [x^n] exp(F^k(x)).
%F A397000 a(n,0,l) = 0^(n-1), b(0,k,l) = 1,
%F A397000 a(n,k,l) = Sum_{j=0..n-1} binomial(n-1,j) * b(j,k+l-1,l) * a(n-j,k-1,l) for k > 0, and
%F A397000 b(n,k,l) = Sum_{j=1..n} binomial(n-1,j-1) * a(j,k,l) * b(n-j,k,l) for n > 0.
%F A397000 These recurrences are computationally expensive; in practice, direct iteration of the defining power series is much faster.
%e A397000 Square array begins:
